Exogenous Forcing in exDE

December 08, 2023

~/exDE/exDE.Rmd

HUB – Roadmap – Library – exDE

\(\odot\)

To implement exogenous forcing in exDE, we were faced with a design question about how much structure was needed. We wanted to build in enough structure so that it would be clear how to add exogenous forcing. We also discovered that at least some structure would be required. Since some variables must be set before others, we wanted to order the function calls to avoid conflicts.

  • Forcing – a longer discussion of exDE design for exogenous forcing

Long Walk

\(\oplus\)

\(\cal W\) - Weather

We start by setting up a model:

library(exDE)
model <- xde_setup("weather", MYZname = "GeRM")

To configure exogenous forcing by weather, it is necessary to do four things:

  1. Turn on abiotic forcing

  2. Turn on weather

  3. Configure the functions that compute variables describing weather.

  4. Configure the functions that compute the effects of variables on various parameters.

Step 1

model = setup_abiotic_forced(model)

The function Abiotic(t, pars) is an S3 function that dispatches on pars$ABIOTIC. By default, ABIOTIC is an empty list and class(ABIOTIC) = NULL, so it has no effect. The first step in setting up forcing is to set class(ABIOTIC) <- "forced". Now the function Abiotic.forced(t, pars) calls two functions:

  • Weather(t,pars)

  • Hydrology(t, pars)

Step 2

model = setup_weather_forced(model)

The function Weather(t, pars) is an S3 function that dispatches on pars$WEATHER. By default, WEATHER is an empty list and class(WEATHER) = NULL, so it has no effect. The first step in setting up forcing is to set class(WEATHER) <- "forced". Now the function Weather.forced(t, pars) calls three functions:

  • Rainfall(t,pars) is an S3 function that dispatches on pars$RAINFALL and by default, class(RAINFALL) = NULL

  • Temperature(t,pars) is an S3 function that dispatches on pars$TEMPERATURE and by default, class(TEMPERATURE]) = NULL

  • Relative_Humidity(t, pars) is an S3 function that dispatches on pars$HUMIDITY and by default, class(HUMIDITY) = NULL

Step 3

Now we need to set up a function that computes Temperature. Here, we set up a sin function: \[ T(t) = 25+ 5 \sin(2\pi t/365) \]

Temperature.eg= function(t, pars){
  pars$temperature =  25 + 5*sin(2*pi*t/365)
  return(pars)
}

Now we set:

class(model$TEMPERATURE) <- "eg"

Step 4 \[\tau(t) = \frac{1}{0.000112 T (T-15.384) \sqrt{35-T}}\] so \[\frac{d\tau(t)}{dt} = -\frac{0.000112\left[-\left(T^2-15.384T\right) \left(35-T\right)^{-1/2} + \sqrt{35-T} \left(2T - 15.384\right)\right]}{\left(0.000112 T (T-15.384) \sqrt{35-T}\right)^2}\]

We need to write the EIP as a function of temperature:

dEIPdt.eg = function(t, pars){
  T = pars$temperature
  1-0.000112*(-(T^2-15.384*T)* (35-T)^(-1/2) + sqrt(35-T)* (2*T - 15.384))/ ((0.000112*T*(T-15.384)*sqrt(35-T)))^2
  return(pars)
}
EIP.eg = function(t, pars){
  T = pars$temperature
  pars$MYZpar$eip <- 1/(0.000112*T*(T-15.384)*sqrt(35-T))
  return(pars)
}
EIPmod = list(name = "eg") 
class(EIPmod) <- "eg"
model$EIPmod = EIPmod

To visualize what is happening, we can use these functions without exDE. First, we plot temperature by time of year:

tt=1:365
T = Temperature.eg(tt,list())$temperature
plot(tt, T, type = "l", xlab = "Time of Year", ylab = "Temperature")

Next, we plot temperature by time of year.

tt=1:365
pars = list(temperature=T, MYZpar=list())
eip = EIP.eg(tt,pars)$MYZpar$eip
plot(tt, eip, type = "l", xlab = "Time of Year", ylab = "EIP")

model <- xde_stable_orbit(model)
with(model$outputs$stable_orbits, with(MYZ, {
  plot(time, Y, col = "purple", type = "l", ylim = range(0, Y)) 
  lines(time, Z, col = "darkred")
}))

with(model$outputs$stable_orbits, with(MYZ, {
  plot(time, y, col = "purple", type = "l", ylim = range(0,y)) 
  lines(time, z, col = "darkred")
}))

\(\cal V\) - Vector Control

Setup

\(\oplus\)

By default, exogenous forcing is turned off. The list objects defining various kinds of forcing are in a nested hierarchy. If the class of a list object is null then there is no need to define anything of the objects it might contain. If a nested list objects is defined, then the list that contains it is turned on and set to forced.

Implementation

The function make_parameters_xde() gets called to create the list that defines a model.

  pars <- setup_exogenous_null(pars)
  pars <- setup_humanbehavior_null(pars)
  pars <- setup_resources_null(pars)
  pars <- setup_vc_null(pars)
  pars <- setup_visitors_null(pars)
  pars <- setup_travel_null(pars)
